MEDIUM|internal/reconcile/emit.go:333|writeFindingsList renders the "(did you mean ...)" path-warning line with reconcile's esc() (emit.go:411), which HTML-escapes but does NOT escape backticks — unlike report's esc() (render.go:388) which does. A reviewer-cited File (or a git-tracked PathSuggestion) containing a backtick passes the raw backtick into report.md, opening a markdown inline code span around injected text. HTML is neutralized but markdown structure is not; the main bullet is safe because it uses codeSpan(), but this warning line uses esc() directly.|Make reconcile's esc() escape backticks identically to report's esc() (append strings.ReplaceAll(s, backtick, "&#96;")), or route the warning-line File/suggestion through codeSpan(). Add a reconcile test feeding a backtick-bearing File AND PathSuggestion through RenderMarkdown asserting no raw backtick survives.|security|30|internal/reconcile/emit.go:326-336 + emit.go:408-411|claude
MEDIUM|internal/reconcile/emit.go:332|The "did you mean" warning-line render is duplicated across two packages: writeFindingsList (emit.go:326-336) and writePathWarning (render.go:321-330), and they have already drifted — report escapes backticks, reconcile does not (see the security item). Two copies of the same security-sensitive format string with divergent escaping is a standing drift hazard; report already centralizes its three views behind one writePathWarning helper, the reconcile copy is an inline fourth implementation.|Extract one shared path-warning renderer taking (file, suggestion string) with a single escaping policy and call it from both writeFindingsList and writePathWarning, collapsing the escaping asymmetry by construction.|maintainability|60|internal/reconcile/emit.go:326-336 + internal/report/render.go:321-330|claude
LOW|internal/stream/suggest.go:93|tier1's multi-candidate branch can suggest a sibling for a cited path that is itself a tracked file but absent on disk (git-tracked yet missing from the working tree). When such a path reaches MissingSuggestion via the existsOutsideOrAbsent branch (validate.go:90-95) and a same-basename sibling is tracked, the loop skips self (c == rel) but returns the sibling as a "correction" — the single-candidate branch guards self (line 88) but the multi-candidate branch does not guard against correcting a path that is itself tracked.|After the scoring loop, if rel itself is in candidates (the cited path is tracked), return "" — a tracked path is never a hallucination to correct regardless of on-disk state. Add a test: indexFromPaths({"a/validate.go","b/validate.go"}); assert MissingSuggestion("a/validate.go") == "".|correctness|30|internal/stream/suggest.go:80-110|claude
LOW|internal/stream/fileindex.go:60|The index doc claims keys are platform-independent because cited paths are normalized via filepath.ToSlash, but ToSlash is a no-op on non-Windows builds (atcr runs on macOS/Linux). A reviewer or Windows-trained LLM citing backslash paths (internal\auth\validate.go) is therefore NOT normalized — Has() and MissingSuggestion() silently return no match and no suggestion.|Replace filepath.ToSlash with an explicit strings.ReplaceAll(p, backslash, "/") (plus ToSlash) in indexFromPaths and the lookup methods so backslashes normalize regardless of build OS. Add a test asserting Has/MissingSuggestion succeed for a backslash-cited path.|error-handling|30|internal/stream/fileindex.go:55-74|claude
LOW|internal/stream/fileindex.go:37|BuildFileIndex collapses every git failure (not-a-repo, git binary missing, corrupt repo, timeout/kill) into return nil with the error discarded entirely. The whole path-hardening feature can be silently disabled in CI with no log or metric signal, making a silent feature-off indistinguishable from the legitimate non-repo case.|Keep the nil-return contract but log the underlying error at debug/warn level before returning nil. Verify by injecting a bogus PATH and asserting the log fires while the index is still nil.|ops|15|internal/stream/fileindex.go:35-41|claude
LOW|internal/stream/fileindex.go:113|Case folding uses strings.ToLower, which the doc calls "Unicode-simple case folding." strings.ToLower is not proper Unicode case folding (no title-case / Turkish dotless-i / German ss / final-sigma handling). Harmless for ASCII Go source paths but the documented contract overstates the guarantee.|Downgrade the comment to "ASCII-lowercase, not full Unicode case folding," or switch to golang.org/x/text/cases.Fold. Lowest-effort correct fix is the comment.|docs|5|internal/stream/fileindex.go:113-121|claude
LOW|internal/stream/suggest.go:120|tier2 computes Levenshtein (O(n*m) with two []rune + two int-row allocations) plus splitStem for every basename in the cited directory, with no length-difference early-out and no memoization across findings citing the same dir. Bounded (one dir, Tier-1 misses only) so not critical, but allocates per comparison.|Add a cheap early-out: skip candidates whose stem length differs from the cited stem by more than floor((1-threshold)*maxlen) before computing Levenshtein (length diff is a lower bound on edit distance). Confirm suggest tests still pass; add a benchmark over a large synthetic dir.|performance|30|internal/stream/suggest.go:114-152|claude
LOW|internal/stream/validate.go:68|The lexical and containment escape checks compare against ".."+filepath.Separator. Correct on the macOS/Linux runtime (filepath.Join/Rel emit OS separators), but brittle: if a future caller passes slash-form paths into filepath.Rel on Windows, the prefix check would mismatch and a ../foo escape could pass the guard. Latent cross-platform fragility, not a live break.|Normalize both sides with filepath.ToSlash and compare against "../", or assert the platform. Add a table test using both separator forms.|security|15|internal/stream/validate.go:60-73 + validate.go:124-141|claude
LOW|internal/reconcile/emit_test.go:175|No test exercises markup injection through PathSuggestion or through File on the warning line specifically. TestRenderMarkdown_BacktickFilePathRendersInert covers only the main codeSpan bullet, and the ShowsPathSuggestion tests use clean suggestions — so the backtick defense does not transfer to the warning line and no test would catch the drift regression.|Add a reconcile-side test feeding backtick/HTML-bearing File AND PathSuggestion through RenderMarkdown asserting no raw backtick survives; add the symmetric assertion on the report side (report/validate_test.go only tests clean suggestions).|testing|30|internal/reconcile/emit_test.go:175-189 + internal/report/validate_test.go:55-98|claude
LOW|internal/reconcile/validate.go:21|validateFindingPaths returns early on empty root, but when root is set and there are zero findings it still shells out to git ls-files to build an index that is never consulted — an avoidable process spawn on empty reviews.|Add if len(findings) == 0 { return } before BuildFileIndex. Micro-optimization, not a correctness issue.|performance|5|internal/reconcile/validate.go:17-25|claude

